        keyFormula: "Accounting = the language of business — it tracks, summarizes, and reports financial activity",
        lesson: "<p>Imagine you run a lemonade stand. Every day you buy lemons, sugar, and cups. Customers hand you cash. At the end of the week, you want to know: did I actually make money, or did I spend more than I earned? <strong>Accounting</strong> is the system that answers that question. It is the process of recording, organizing, and reporting a business's financial activity so people can make smart decisions.</p><p>So who actually cares about this information? Lots of people. <strong>Business owners</strong> need it to know if they are profitable. <strong>Investors</strong> need it to decide whether to put their money into a company. <strong>Banks</strong> need it before they approve a loan. Even the <strong>government</strong> needs it to make sure you are paying the right amount of taxes. Accounting is often called the \"language of business\" because it is how all these groups communicate about money.</p><p>You might hear the words <strong>bookkeeping</strong> and <strong>accounting</strong> used as though they mean the same thing, but they are different. Bookkeeping is the day-to-day work of recording transactions — typing in receipts, logging payments, keeping everything organized. Think of a bookkeeper as the person who writes down every play in a football game. An <strong>accountant</strong>, on the other hand, is like the coach who studies all those notes, spots patterns, and makes strategic decisions. Accountants analyze the data, prepare financial reports, and give advice.</p><p>There are a few main branches of accounting you should know about. <strong>Financial accounting</strong> focuses on preparing reports for people outside the company, like investors and regulators. <strong>Managerial accounting</strong> creates reports for people inside the company to help with planning and decision-making. <strong>Tax accounting</strong> deals with preparing tax returns and following tax laws. No matter which branch, the goal is the same: turn raw financial data into useful information.</p><p>Here is the big takeaway: accounting exists because businesses need a reliable, organized way to track what is happening with their money. Without it, running a business would be like driving with your eyes closed. You might move forward for a while, but eventually you are going to crash.</p>",
