        id: "basics-accounting-equation",
        title: "The Accounting Equation",
        cpaSection: "BASICS",
        objectives: ["State the accounting equation and explain each component","Use a real-world analogy to understand assets, liabilities, and equity","Show how every transaction keeps the equation in balance"],
        keyFormula: "Assets = Liabilities + Owner's Equity",
        lesson: "<p>Every single thing in accounting is built on one simple idea: <strong>Assets = Liabilities + Owner's Equity</strong>. This is called the <strong>accounting equation</strong>, and it must always stay in balance — like a seesaw that never tips to one side.</p><p>Let's break it down with a house analogy. Say you buy a house worth $300,000. You put down $60,000 of your own money and borrow $240,000 from the bank. The house is your <strong>asset</strong> — something valuable that you own. The bank loan is your <strong>liability</strong> — something you owe to someone else. And that $60,000 you put in? That is your <strong>equity</strong> — your personal stake, or what is left over after you subtract what you owe from what you own. So: $300,000 (asset) = $240,000 (liability) + $60,000 (equity). The equation balances perfectly.</p><p><strong>Assets</strong> are resources a business owns or controls that have value. Cash, equipment, buildings, inventory, and even money that customers owe you (called accounts receivable) are all assets. <strong>Liabilities</strong> are debts or obligations — money the business owes to others. Loans, unpaid bills, and wages you owe employees are liabilities. <strong>Owner's equity</strong> (also called stockholders' equity in a corporation) is what is left for the owners after all the debts are paid off. It represents the owner's claim on the business.</p><p>Here is the magic: every transaction a business makes affects at least two things in this equation, and the equation always stays balanced. If you borrow $10,000 from a bank, your cash (an asset) goes up by $10,000, and your loan (a liability) also goes up by $10,000. Both sides increase equally. If you use $5,000 cash to buy equipment, one asset (cash) goes down while another asset (equipment) goes up — the total stays the same.</p><p>Think of the accounting equation as the foundation of a building. If the foundation is crooked, everything built on top of it will be crooked too. Every journal entry, every financial statement, and every audit ultimately traces back to this one equation staying in balance.</p>",
