        keyFormula: "Date + Account(s) Debited + Account(s) Credited + Amounts + Description = Journal Entry",
        lesson: "<p>A <strong>journal entry</strong> is how you officially record a business transaction in your accounting system. Think of it like writing in a diary — except instead of \"Dear Diary, today was a good day,\" you are writing \"Today we received $500 cash for services we performed.\" Every financial event that affects your business gets written down as a journal entry.</p><p>Every journal entry has the same basic parts. First, the <strong>date</strong> of the transaction. Second, the <strong>accounts affected</strong> — at least one account will be debited and at least one will be credited. Third, the <strong>dollar amounts</strong>. And fourth, a brief <strong>description</strong> (sometimes called a narration or memo) explaining what happened. The debited accounts are listed first and written flush left, while the credited accounts are indented slightly to the right. This formatting makes it easy to scan entries quickly.</p><p>Let's walk through an example. On January 5, your business pays $1,200 for three months of office rent in advance. You would write: Date — January 5. Debit <strong>Prepaid Rent</strong> $1,200 (an asset — you now have a future benefit). Credit <strong>Cash</strong> $1,200 (an asset — your cash decreased). Description: \"Paid three months of office rent in advance.\" Notice that debits equal credits. They always must.</p><p>The book where you record all these entries is called the <strong>general journal</strong>. It is sometimes called the \"book of original entry\" because it is the first place every transaction is written down. Later, this information gets transferred (or \"posted\") to individual accounts in the ledger — but we will cover that in the next lesson.</p><p>A common beginner mistake is forgetting to record both sides of a transaction. If you only record the debit and skip the credit, your books will be out of balance. Always ask yourself two questions: what is being received or increasing, and what is being given up or decreasing? Answer both, and you will have a correct journal entry every time.</p>",
        practiceTip: "Before writing a journal entry, pause and ask: what did the business receive, and what did it give up? The answer will tell you exactly which accounts to debit and credit."
