        keyFormula: "T-Account: Left side = Debits, Right side = Credits; Balance = difference between the two sides",
        lesson: "<p>A <strong>T-account</strong> is the simplest way to visualize what is happening inside an account. Draw a big letter T on a piece of paper. Write the account name on top. The left side is for <strong>debits</strong>, and the right side is for <strong>credits</strong>. That is it. It is a quick sketch that helps you see at a glance how much has gone in and out of any account.</p><p>Let's say you want to track your Cash account. At the start of the month, you have $5,000. During the month, you receive $3,000 from customers (debit side — cash is an asset, so increases go on the left) and pay $2,000 for expenses (credit side — decreases go on the right). Your T-account now shows $8,000 on the debit side and $2,000 on the credit side. The <strong>balance</strong> is $8,000 minus $2,000 = $6,000. Since the debit side is larger, we say Cash has a <strong>debit balance</strong> of $6,000.</p><p>Now, one T-account by itself is useful, but a business has dozens or hundreds of accounts. When you put them all together in one organized place, you get the <strong>general ledger</strong>. The ledger is the master record of every account and its running balance. Think of the journal (from the previous lesson) as your raw diary entries, and the ledger as a neatly organized summary grouped by account.</p><p>The process of transferring information from the journal to the ledger is called <strong>posting</strong>. After you write a journal entry, you take each line and post it to the correct T-account in the ledger. For example, if your journal entry debits Cash and credits Service Revenue, you go to the Cash T-account and add the amount on the debit side, then go to the Service Revenue T-account and add the amount on the credit side.</p><p>T-accounts are mostly a learning tool — modern software does all this automatically. But understanding them is incredibly valuable because they give you a mental picture of how money flows through accounts. When something does not look right in your books, sketching a quick T-account can help you find the error fast.</p>",
