        keyFormula: "Total Debits = Total Credits (if not, there is an error somewhere)",
        lesson: "<p>You have recorded journal entries and posted them to the ledger. Now it is time to check your work. A <strong>trial balance</strong> is a list of every account in your ledger along with its balance, arranged in two columns: debits on the left, credits on the right. Then you add up each column. If the totals match, your books are <strong>in balance</strong>. If they do not match, you know something went wrong somewhere.</p><p>Think of a trial balance like a spell-check for your accounting. It does not guarantee that everything is perfect, but it catches a lot of common mistakes. Preparing one is simple: list every account from the ledger, write its debit or credit balance in the correct column, and total each column. Assets, expenses, and dividends normally have debit balances. Liabilities, equity, and revenue normally have credit balances.</p><p>Here is an important warning: a trial balance that balances does <strong>not</strong> mean your books are error-free. It only proves that total debits equal total credits. There are several errors it will not catch. If you accidentally recorded a transaction in the wrong account (say you debited Supplies instead of Equipment), both accounts are in the right column — the trial balance still balances. If you completely forgot to record a transaction, there is nothing to catch because nothing is there. And if you recorded the same transaction twice, debits and credits are both doubled equally, so the totals still match.</p><p>What <strong>will</strong> a trial balance catch? Any time you posted a debit without a matching credit, or wrote down the wrong amount on one side but not the other, the two columns will not add up. These are called <strong>one-sided errors</strong>, and the trial balance is great at flagging them.</p><p>In practice, businesses prepare a trial balance at the end of each accounting period — monthly, quarterly, or yearly — before they create financial statements. It is a checkpoint that says, \"Okay, the basic math checks out. Let's move on to the next step.\" It is not the final answer, but it is an essential safety net along the way.</p>",
        practiceTip: "If your trial balance does not balance, check for these common errors first: transposed numbers (writing 540 instead of 450), posting to the wrong column, or forgetting to post one side of a journal entry."
